  <span id="freeText8358988474931306120" style="display:none"> Hafiz This edition was translated by Herman Bicknell Publisher: Floating Press, <br />The Publication Date:01/07/2012<br /><br />The 1928 edition's Preface by E. Denison Ross explained the three different types of translation:<br />1. Literal prose translations.<br />2. Translations in which either the metre or the mono-rhyme or both together are imitated.<br />3. Free translations into English verse. Many English translators have tried their hand at the poems of Hafiz, and the three varieties of translation referred to have all been attempted.<br />"Colonel Wilberforce-Clarke in 1891 published a complete prose translation with copious notes and an exhaustive commentary. This translation is so slavishly literal as to be mostly unreadable except as a crib. . . . Mr. Walter Leaf published twenty-eight Versions from Hafiz, in which he attempted to reproduce both the metre and the mono-rhyme of the Persian, and probably came as near to success as is possible in the circumstances. . . . <u>Herman Bicknell . . . while making each verse of his translation correspond with its original, adopted the rhyming couplets and did not attempt to preserve the mono-rhyme.</u> Finally there is the free translation into English verse without regard to the form, metre or rhyme of the original. Numerous efforts have been made in this style, but those of Gertrude Bell are incomparably the best." (pp. 18-19)*<br /><br />*Bell Lowthian Gertrude. (1928). <i>Poems From The Divan Of Hafiz</i>. London: William Heinemann.<br /><br />". . . my Brother [Herman Bicknell] deeming it useless to attempt an exact imitation of either the monorhyme of the Odes or the strange harmony of the Persian rhythm, assured me that the obstacles in the way of a perfect translation of Háfiz were so serious as to prevent him from aspiring to achieve more than a faithful rendering of the literal meaning, and to give a tolerable idea of the construction." Bicknell, A. S. (1875). Preface. In Háfiz &amp; H. Bicknell <i> Háfiz of Shiraz <br />Selections From His Poems</i> (p.14). London: Turner &amp; Co.<br /><br />Introduction by Herman Bicknell - 4 Stars <br /><br />The footnotes helped quite a bit in understanding the poems.<br />I. "Alá yá ayyuh'a s-Sáki!"— pass round and offer thou the bowl. - 3.5 Stars <br />II. Thou whose features clearly-beaming make the moon of Beauty bright. - 4 Stars <br />III. Sáki, come! my bowl rekindle with the light of lustrous wine: - 3 Stars <br />IV. Come, Súfí, and behold my bowl, whose rays as a pure mirror shine, - 4 Stars <br />V. Up, Sáki !—let the goblet flow; Strew with dust the head of our earthly woe! - 5 Stars <br />VI. My heart no longer brooks my hand : sages, aid for God my woe! - 3 Stars <br />VII. Arrayed in youthful splendour, the orchard smiles again; - 4 Stars <br />VIII. If the Shirázian Turk would deign to take my heart within his hand, - 3.5 Stars<br />IX. O! East my story gently tell to yonder slender-shaped gazelle: - 3.5 Stars <br />X. Last night our Pir, the mosque foresaking, straight to the wine-house shaped his way; - 3.5 Stars <br />XI. Who to the sultan's courtiers hence will my prayer convey? - 3.5 Stars <br />XII. Oh! where are deeds of virtue and this frail spirit where ? - 4 Stars <br />XIII. I, as thou knowst, went forth, and my heart with sorrow oppressed, - 4 Stars <br />XIV. At eve a son of song—his heart be cheerful long!— - 4 Stars <br />XV. To lovers since thy beauty cried, to call them to thy presence high, - 3.5 Stars <br />XVI. I said: "O Monarch of the lovely, a stranger seeks thy grace this day." - 3.5 Stars <br />XVII. Tis morn; the clouds a ceiling make: - 4 Stars <br />XVIII. The morning of my fortune dawns: where have they placed the sun-like bowl? - 5 Stars <br />XIX. Lo! from thy love's enchanting bowers Rizván's bright gardens fresher grow; - 3.5 Stars <br />XX. I swear—my master's soul bear witness, faith of old times and promise leal!— - 4.5 Stars <br />XXI. I have a nest to hold thee, 'tis in my eye's bright centre: - 4 Stars <br />XXII. Veiled in my heart my fervent love for him dwells, - 3 Stars <br />XXIII. Prone at my friend's high gates, my Will it's head lays still: - 2.5 Stars <br />XXIV. The zealot of an outward zeal ignores what in my heart is pent: - 2 Stars <br />XXV. Breeze of the morn, if hence to the land thou fleet—Of my friend, - 3.5 Stars <br />XXVI. Come hither! hope's unsteady palace is trembling in its place; - 3 Stars <br />XXVII. My breast has its flowers, my palms has its cup, my Loved one smiles and is gay; - 4 Stars <br />XXVIII. Wherefore should cypress and pine adorn my garden's glade? - 3.5 Stars <br />XXIX. Who of a Heaven on earth can tell, pure as the cell— Of dervishes? - 3 Stars <br />XXX. My friend to the Magian's cloister came with a goblet grasped in his hand: - 3 Stars <br />XXXI. In blossom is the crimson rose, and the rapt bulbul trills his song; - 3 Stars <br />XXXII. With ruffled books, with sweat-drops dripping, beaming with smiles, and from the cup, - 4 Stars <br />XXXIII. A mate who in the present age from all deceit is free, - 4 Stars <br />XXXIV. Seek in my brain no corner where good advice may dwell; - 3.5 Stars <br />XXXV. Now on the rose's palm the cup limpid with limpid wine is brimming, - 3.5 Stars <br />XXXVI. To him who has seclusion chosen, of new and strange— What need? - 4.5 Stars <br />XXXVII. To me by the free lily once was told: - 3 Stars <br />XXXVIII. With friends 'twere impoliteness deemed to boast oneself as skilled; - 3.5 Stars <br />XXXIX. Aught fairer than parterre and spring with bliss, oh! say—What is it? - 4 Stars <br />XL. Glassed in that cheek, as the cheek's smile o'erstole, - 4.5 Stars <br />XLI. Though wine incites to jocund mirth, and winds through flowers are sighing, - 3.5 Stars <br />XLII. 'Tis a deep charm which wakes the lover's flame, - 5 Stars <br /><br />My conclusion is that although I personally prefer Gertrude Bell's translations overall I found Bicknell's first lines of the ghazals both beautifully compelling insightful.</span>
