<span id="freeTextContainer6280439198582864039">The poetry of Hafiz stands on its own merit. It is among the greatest gifts God has given to mankind. <br/><br/>“Arise, oh Cup-bearer, rise! And bring<br/>To lips that are thirsting the bowl they praise,<br/>For it seemed that love was an easy thing,<br/>But my feet have fallen on difficult ways.<br/> I have prayed the wind o’er my heart to fling<br/>The fragrance of musk in her hair that sleeps—<br/>In the night of her hair—yet no fragrance stays<br/>The tears of my heart’s blood my sad heart weeps. <br/><br/>&quot;Dowered is my mistress, a beggar am I;</span>
  <span id="freeText6280439198582864039" style="display:none">The poetry of Hafiz stands on its own merit. It is among the greatest gifts God has given to mankind. <br /><br />“Arise, oh Cup-bearer, rise! And bring<br />To lips that are thirsting the bowl they praise,<br />For it seemed that love was an easy thing,<br />But my feet have fallen on difficult ways.<br /> I have prayed the wind o’er my heart to fling<br />The fragrance of musk in her hair that sleeps—<br />In the night of her hair—yet no fragrance stays<br />The tears of my heart’s blood my sad heart weeps. <br /><br />"Dowered is my mistress, a beggar am I;<br /> What shall I bring her? A beautiful face<br />Needs nor jewel nor mole nor the tiring-maid’s art.” <br /><br /> “From out the street of [my beloved….],<br />Oh wind, bring perfumes sweet to me<br />For I am sick and pale with woe;<br />Oh bring me rest from misery!<br />The dust that lies before her door,<br />Love’s long desired elixir, pour <br />Upon this wasted heart of mine—<br />Bring me a promise and a sign!” (Hafiz xx)<br /><br /> “I cease not from desire till my desire <br />Is satisfied; or let my mouth attain<br />My love’s red mouth, or let my soul expire,<br />Sighed from those lips that sought her lips in vain.<br />Others may find another love as fair; <br />Upon her threshold I have laid my head,<br />The dust shall cover me, still lying there,<br />When from my body life and love have fled. (xxxviii)<br /><br /> “If seekers after rubies there were none, <br />Still to the dark mines where the gems had lain<br />Would pierce, as he was wont, the radiant sun,<br />Setting the stones ablaze. <br /> Would’st hide the stain <br />Of my heart’s blood? Blood-red the ruby glows<br />(And whence it came my wounded bosom knows)<br />Upon thy lips to show what thou hast done.” <br />Hafiz <br /><br /> Having written my thesis for my second MA on Orientalist representations of Sufism, there is much I could say about Gertrude Bell’s introduction and translation of Hafiz. The introduction is standard orientalist fare in its explanation of Sufism and its “non-Islamic” origins, and this really could be expected from the classical orientalist/Arabist/imperial tool that was Gertrude Bell, contemporary of Lawrence of Arabia, though she backed the Sa’ud family of Najd over Lawrence Hijazi shareefs. In fact, her writing on Sufism is superficial and repulsive—an insult to the noble tradition that is the core of the spiritual teachings of Islam. She would set Sufism up to be something it is not—a projection of her Orientalist training and the vast corpus of convoluted literature that was an inheritor and participant in. While the historical background painting the truly violent times that Hafiz inhabited (the times of Timurlane among others) is valuable, her writing on the origins of Sufism and its doctrines truly show that she did not spend time spending classical Islamic theology—most of her scholarly missteps originate in this abysmal ignorance—compounded, perhaps, by her time with the Najdis and their deviant scholarship. Bell actually says: “To many Persians, Hafiz occupies the place that is filled by Shakespeare in the minds of many Englishmen. It may be a national prejudice, but I cannot believe that the mental food supplied by the Oriental is as good as the other. But, then, our appetites are not the same.” (22) My critiques of Bell’s Orientalist background aside, parts of her introduction do prepare one well for the poem, and some of her notes following are actually very useful, though often so incredibly biased as to almost be a textbook study in hubris and bigotry. <br /><br />As I said, sometimes Bell's notes do add to the understanding of the text. A particularly beautiful example occurs in relation to the following lines: “Thy mouth the fountain where Life’s waters flow,A dimpled well of tears is set below, And death lies near to life thy lovers know, But know in vain!” (iv) Bell’s notes: The Persians describe the dimple in the chin of their mistress as a dangerous well filled with her lover’s tears, into which, when he approaches her mouth, he may fall and be drowned. (77)</span>
